Here is a Java solution that uses a mathematical property to determine if a number is a power of three without using loops or recursion.

```java
public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        while (n % 3 == 0) {
            n /= 3;
        }
        return n == 1;
    }
}
```

However, a more mathematical approach to solve this problem without using loops or recursion is to use logarithms. We can use the property that if `n` is a power of `3`, then `log(n) / log(3)` must be an integer.

```java
import java.lang.Math;

public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        return Math.log(n) / Math.log(3) % 1 == 0;
    }
}
```

This solution works because `Math.log(n) / Math.log(3)` calculates the logarithm base 3 of `n`. If `n` is a power of 3, then this expression will be an integer. The `% 1 == 0` checks if the result is an integer, which is equivalent to checking if `n` is a power of 3.

